# ARIA Accessibility

Ensure UI is compatible with screen readers and assistive tech by following these patterns.

## Prefer Semantic HTML

Use native elements instead of ARIA when possible. Semantic HTML carries built-in roles and states.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD – div with ARIA role
<div role="button" onClick={handleClick}>Submit</div>

// ✅ GOOD – native element
<button type="button" onClick={handleClick}>Submit</button>
```

- Use `<button>` for actions, `<a>` for navigation, `<nav>` for nav regions, `<main>` for main content.
- Use heading hierarchy (`h1` → `h2` → `h3`) correctly.

## Icon-Only Buttons

Every icon-only or image-only control must have an accessible name.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD – no label
<button onClick={onClose}><IconX /></button>

// ✅ GOOD – aria-label
<button onClick={onClose} aria-label="Close">
  <IconX aria-hidden />
</button>
```

- Add `aria-hidden` to purely decorative icons so they are not announced twice.

## Expandable Controls

Expose expanded/collapsed state to assistive tech.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
<button
  aria-expanded={isOpen}
  aria-haspopup="dialog"
  aria-controls="my-dialog-id"
  onClick={toggle}
>
  Open menu
</button>
```

- Use `aria-expanded` for toggles, accordions, and disclosure widgets.
- Use `aria-haspopup` when the control opens a menu, dialog, or listbox.

## Toggle Buttons

Use `aria-pressed` for on/off toggles (e.g. mute, favourite).

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
<button
  aria-pressed={isMuted}
  onClick={toggleMute}
  aria-label={isMuted ? "Unmute" : "Mute"}
>
  {isMuted ? <IconVolumeOff /> : <IconVolume />}
</button>
```

## Form Fields and Validation

- Every form control needs a visible label (use `<label>` with `htmlFor`, or `aria-label` / `aria-labelledby`).
- For errors: use `aria-invalid="true"` and `aria-errormessage` (or `aria-describedby`) linking to the error text.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
<label htmlFor="email">Email</label>
<input
  id="email"
  type="email"
  aria-invalid={!!error}
  aria-describedby={error ? "email-error" : undefined}
/>
{error ? <span id="email-error" role="alert">{error}</span> : null}
```

## Modals and Dialogs

- Trap focus inside the dialog and return focus on close.
- Add `aria-modal="true"` and `role="dialog"` (or use a dialog component that does this).
- Provide `aria-labelledby` (and optionally `aria-describedby`) for the dialog.

## Live Regions

For dynamic updates (alerts, notifications, loading states) that should be announced:

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD – announce important updates
<div aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true">
  {statusMessage}
</div>
```

- Use `aria-live="polite"` for non-urgent updates; `aria-live="assertive"` sparingly.
- Use `aria-atomic="true"` when the entire region should be read as one unit.

## Decorative Content

Hide purely decorative elements from screen readers:

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
<span aria-hidden="true"><IconCheck className="decorative" /></span>
```

## Avoid Redundant ARIA

Do not add ARIA that repeats what HTML already provides.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD – redundant
<button role="button" aria-label="Click me">Click me</button>

// ✅ GOOD – native semantics suffice
<button>Click me</button>
```

## Summary

| Pattern | Do | Avoid |
|--------|----|-------|
| Buttons | `<button>` or `<a>` with clear text/label | `div` + `onClick`, icon-only without `aria-label` |
| Expandables | `aria-expanded`, `aria-haspopup` | Missing state for toggles |
| Forms | `<label>`, `aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby` | Unlabelled inputs, no error association |
| Dialogs | Focus trap, `aria-modal`, `aria-labelledby` | Untrapped focus, missing labels |
| Decorative | `aria-hidden` | Announcing non-meaningful content |
